# AzerothCore Development Standards

## Project context

- **Community / server**: Old Man Warcraft — oldmanwarcraft.com; production WoW WotLK 3.3.5a private server.
- **Framework**: AzerothCore WotLK 3.3.5a; this tree is a **custom fork** with additional modules and patches.
- **Primary module focus**: mod-playerbots (AI-driven bots); many other custom modules live under `modules/`.
- **Languages**: C++ (core), SQL (database), Lua (where modules use it).
- **Databases**: acore_world (shared content), acore_characters (per realm), acore_playerbots (per realm, if used), acore_auth (shared)—plus any module-specific tables.
- **Git remotes**: **GitLab** = org **origin** for daily work; **GitHub** = **upstream** for AzerothCore and many stock modules. Paths under `modules/` are often **separate Git repositories**—sync and merge **per module** as well as for the core repo.
- **This host**: **Production only** (no local development realm). Validate with backups, maintenance windows, off-host testing, dry runs, and log review—not “always test on 8086 first.”
- **Operational documentation**: **Notion** holds server/runbook-style detail; use the **Notion MCP** to **look up** host-specific facts instead of guessing (see `.cursor/rules/mcp-usage.mdc`).
- **Live data / SOAP / wiki helpers**: When the **azerothcore** MCP is connected, prefer it for spell proc diagnosis, SmartAI traces, DB queries, and wiki search—**after** checking production safety and SOAP policy.
- **MCP catalog**: Use **all** configured MCP tools where they fit the task (GitLab, Notion, OMW `omw_*`, fetch, firecrawl, exa, deepwiki, sequential-thinking, browser)—see `.cursor/reference/mcp-tools-inventory.md` and `.cursor/rules/mcp-usage.mdc`.
- **More detail**: `.cursor/reference/PROJECT_SUMMARY.md`, `.cursor/skills/`, `CLAUDE.md`.

## C++ code standards

<cpp_standards>
- Follow AzerothCore C++ conventions for this fork
- **Naming**: Classes=PascalCase, Functions=camelCase, Variables=camelCase, Constants=UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- **Indentation**: 4 spaces (no tabs)
- **Line length**: Max 120 characters
- **Braces**: Allman style (opening brace on new line)
- **Memory**: Use std::unique_ptr/std::shared_ptr; avoid raw owning pointers
- **Error handling**: Assertions for logic errors; exceptions where the codebase already uses them for recoverable cases
- **Comments**: Doxygen-style for public APIs; explain WHY not WHAT
</cpp_standards>

## Database rules

<database_rules>
- **World database** (`acore_world`): Shared—changes affect all realms using it. Schedule invasive work off-peak; backup first; use transactions for multi-step changes.
- **Character / playerbots DBs**: Realm-specific—avoid hand-editing; prefer in-game flows and supported tools unless you fully understand the schema.
- **Always backup** before major schema or bulk data changes (`mysqldump` or your standard procedure).
- **Use transactions** for multi-table updates: START TRANSACTION / COMMIT.
- **Document** non-obvious SQL (comments, changelog, or module README).
- **Verify integrity** after bulk updates (counts, spot checks, logs).
</database_rules>

## SmartAI scripting

<smartai_rules>
- Use `SMART_EVENT_JUST_CREATED` (63) for initialization, not RESPAWN
- Minimize `SMART_EVENT_UPDATE_IC` (0) and `SMART_EVENT_UPDATE_OOC` (1) — they fire every update
- Always set `event_phase_mask >= 1` (0 means never triggers)
- Always set `event_chance > 0` (0 means never triggers)
- Use conditions to filter unnecessary event triggers
- Document event phases in comments for complex scripts
- Test phase transitions thoroughly — bugs cause infinite loops
- Use `SMART_EVENT_LINK` (61) for sequential actions
</smartai_rules>

## Spell configuration

<spell_rules>
- Verify proc flags match spell intent — incorrect flags cause unintended triggers
- Use `PROC_SPELL_PHASE_HIT` (0x2) for damage procs, `PROC_SPELL_PHASE_CAST` (0x1) for cast-time effects
- Spell family masks must match class/school for spellmod interactions
- Test proc interactions with triggered spells — some have restrictions
- Document proc conditions in spell_proc comments
- Check for conflicting proc configurations before deployment
</spell_rules>

## Module development

<module_rules>
- Proper `CMakeLists.txt` listing all sources/headers
- Configuration: safe defaults (usually disabled), documented in `.conf.dist`
- Database schema in `data/sql/base/`, updates in `data/sql/updates/`
- Update script naming: `YYYY_MM_DD_XX_description.sql`
- Module must compile without warnings where feasible
- Validate on **this production stack** with care: backup, rollback plan, and log monitoring (or validate off-host when possible)
- Document features in README.md
</module_rules>

## Testing and deployment (production host)

<testing_rules>
- **No local dev realm on this host** — use backups, staged SQL, maintenance windows, and post-deploy log checks (`Server.log`, `Errors.log`, and paths your layout uses e.g. `/data/logs` if bound there).
- Prefer **low-risk ordering**: compile → apply SQL → restart during agreed window → monitor.
- **Never** treat production character data as disposable; **never** skip rollback planning for shared `acore_world` changes.
- After deploy: grep logs for errors, verify modules loaded, spot-check critical in-game flows.
- Rollback: stop server → restore DB backup if needed → revert binary/config → document incident.
</testing_rules>

## Safety and stability

<safety_rules>
- **Never** modify `creature_template` directly — use `UPDATE_TEMPLATE` action
- **Never** delete rows without understanding dependencies
- **Never** change primary keys in existing records casually
- **Never** run heavy or risky `acore_world` work during peak hours without agreement
- **Never** enable noisy debug logging in production without reason
- Document dangerous operations
- **CRITICAL**: Defensive null checks in all bot group operations (see `playerbots-rules.mdc`)
- **CRITICAL**: Avoid arena group formation with bots until race condition is fixed
- **CRITICAL**: Avoid guild operations with bots until null check issues are patched
</safety_rules>

